on system obscures a genuine understanding of the very nature of subordination. Acknowledging that categorization is crucial and unavoidable in a world of practical problems and day-to-day conflicts, Ruth Colker shows how categories can and must be improved for the good of all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDiscriminationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aDiscrimination. 0aLawxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aLaw. 0aMinoritiesxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aMinoritiesxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aMinorities. 0aSexual orientationzUnited States. 0aSexual orientation. 7aLAW / Gender & the Law.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107169240 cprintz978081471520840uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814772195.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814772195423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814772195/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK